<h2>Front-End Style Guides</h2>
<p>The first one I got into from this collection was <strong><a href="http://www.fivesimplesteps.com/products/front-end-style-guides" target="_blank">Front-End Style Guides</a></strong> by Anna Debenham.</p>
<p>Now the reason I was excited to get into this one right away was the fact that I'm currently working on a pretty big front-end project collaborating with a friend of mine, and it'll be a project that goes on for a while. We actually started implementing an interactive style guide a couple of weeks ago for us to both add components to and adhere to whilst developing.</p>
<p>This book is ideal for someone like me just having a first go at this sort of thing and the detail the author goes into about the different types of style guide that you can create quite helped me redefine mine. It also makes me want to spend time going back and creating style guides for a few projects at my day job, but alas we'll never have the time to go back and do it!</p>

<blockquote class="pullquote">Presenting a living style guide or a pattern portfolio will be a great way to present work in progress.</blockquote>

<p>But they are incredibly useful tools and this book shows that as a resource for designers, initial developers and those who go on to pick up a project after launch to maintain it. I'll be spending some time creating a boilerplate style guide for all my personal projects from now and a bespoke one for each website I make.</p>
<p>Another thing I enjoyed about this book is the vast amount of amazing resources it offers links to such as MailChimp's <a href="http://voiceandtone.com/" target="_blank">Voice &amp; Tone</a>, the <a href="http://www.lime-management.com/app_themes/limemanagementuk/resources/brand_guidelines.pdf" target="_blank">British Airways style guide</a> and <a href="http://mezzoblue.com/downloads/markupguide/" target="_blank">Dave Shea's style guide</a> - all of which I had to leave the book for a good while and pore over each guide.</p>
<p>Reading the chapter on pattern primers/portfolios has also now changed the way I've begun to think about presenting mockups to clients - something I tend to stay away from going into too much detail on, preferring a static design or two and then moving swiftly on to an interactive HTML/CSS mockup. Presenting a living style guide or a pattern portfolio will be a great way to present work in progress to a client and I'll certainly be trying it from now on.</p>
<p>I may be putting a style guide for this site and my new aforementioned project online in the near future, so I'll link back to it here.</p>
