<h2>Experiments for Designers</h2>
<p>Recently I've been getting quite into usability studies and methods of experimenting with user interaction so this <a href="http://www.fivesimplesteps.com/products/experiments-for-designers" target="_blank">Pocket Guide to Experiments for Designers</a> seemed like an apt choice to begin with when I was notified that the second part of the five simple steps collection four was released.</p>
<p>As soon as I saw the first chapter, entitled "Experiments using A/B tests", I knew that this book would give me some valuable insights on user testing as I'd wanted to try out Google's A/B testing tool on one of our apps at work when I get the chance.</p>
<p>This initial chapter offers an explanation of this form of test and explains clearly with the use of case studies how useful it can be and summarises its uses along with giving valuable resources for further reading on the subject&hellip;bookmarked!</p>
<p>Colin McFarland goes on to spark confidence in the usage of testing experiments in the reader and urges them to continue and find out what they can offer to designers and why we should start using them straight away, stating: </p>

<blockquote class="pullquote">I believe that to discover the value of new and innovative ideas, designers should follow their curiosity and intuition: create experiments, be open to failure and iterate quickly.</blockquote>

<p>An inspiring mantra that I could easily stick up on my board at work.</p>
<p>Following this, the author shows the mindset that we as designers should take in order to be successful in implementing user experiments and fleshes out quotable key points that again I should probably write on flash cards for my board in order to drill them in and constantly keep them in mind!</p>
<p>One of my favourite analogies from this book is the <em>Desire Paths</em> story - something that I notice and find curious all the time in the world around me.</p>
<p>Again the author reaffirms his ideas with high profile case studies, showing the reader the true value of the experiments undertaken before moving on to giving a robust framework for us to use and follow.</p>
<p>I especially appreciate the section on timeframes which will hopefully help me to convince management to allow time for user testing and show how valuable it can be, even if only one day per month is dedicated to it!</p>
<p>Colin closes the pocket guide with a chapter on the implications for designers, to show that testing won't magically fix problems but should be utilised as a method to improve the broader goals of a product, and ends with some great advice for us. <small>I won't ruin the end - buy it!</small></p>
